audioContentItems.fileTranscript: In this sym, we will review how the UCSL application varies based on state.
Reminder that we can not C O P whole life applications for Connecticut or Montana.
New York has its own application for our Guaranteed Whole Life policy. We’ll go into detail on New York later.
The states in red on the map have some different verbatim messages that will appear in the e App.
Remember that these boxes are verbatim statements.
You should not try to memorize these, as they may change for each state.
Always be sure to read what's on your screen word for word.
One such example is with California, the final application verbatim has an additional paragraph regarding fraud.
This allows us to be compliant with California law. The fraud statement is also provided in the policy documents.
Again, this is why you should not memorize verbatims. Simply follow the application.
Another California law requires we obtain an email address from our California elders (which is age 65 or older) so we can send them pertinent disclosures before the application is completed.
To comply with the California law, there is a verbatim early in the application regarding consent to electronic delivery and e-signature.
The verbatim and email address field is mandatory, and the e-app will prevent you from continuing the application if you do not enter in a valid customer email address.
Once you have entered the email address in the box you must press the Send button. If you don’t press this button, the e-app will prevent you from continuing the application.
If the email fails to send, the Send button will turn red and will say Fail.
The e-app will prevent you from moving forward until an email has successfully been sent.
If the email successfully sends, the Send button will turn green and will say Sent.
Once you have received the green Sent message, you need to ask the customer to verbally confirm they received the email.
This is what the email that the customer receives looks like.
Here’s another question that will only appear during the application in certain states.
These states have state special questions and verbiage that is required to be read about accessing PDF files via the internet and providing their consent to receive electronic documents.
The state requires we review this electronic consent.
We're asking if they can access the internet in any shape or form.
If they say no, you can clarify by asking if they have access to the internet (smart phone, library, etc.).

If they still answer No, you will need to explain to the applicant that if they are not able to access the internet, or do not provide their consent, you will not be able to take their application over the phone and it will need to be mailed to them. This may delay the processing time and the effective date of their policy.
Let’s practice a state specific scenario! Click the arrow when you are ready to begin.
Have you received an application packet?
No.
Are you able to open, view and save P D F files via the internet?

I am required to obtain your consent for the delivery of electronic documents to you whether through the internet, email, web, text, instant message, digital media or the like. Your consent applies to all documents Mutual of Omaha may be required to deliver to you in writing. Any document provided to you electronically may be provided in paper upon your request. You may withdraw your consent at any time. If you withdraw your consent, I will not be able to complete your application over the phone and I will need to mail you a paper application. You may withdraw your consent, update your contact information or obtain a paper copy of any document for no charge, by contacting (800) 775-6000. You will need access to a computer or other device which provides internet access or email, as well as the ability to open, view and save a PDF, text or html file.
